6lq.title: Vector arithmetic
6lq.clickbait: Vectors: what they are, and how to add and scale them.
6lq.text:
A vector is like an arrow, and has a direction and a magnitude. They are used in [geometry geometry] to describe the relative positions of different points, and in physics to represent quantities such as [velocity velocities], [force forces], and [momentum momentum]. They are studied in mathematics in [3tr linear algebra] as belonging in a [3w0 vector space]. 

To study vectors, we can draw geometric figures, which have the advantage of being visual and intuitive, and show how vectors relate to the physical world. However, as the applications of vectors increase in complexity, it becomes easier for us (and computers) to work with vectors algebraically. The algebra also allows us to be more precise. So we will learn how to use both together.

# Points
We'll start with some points:

![three points](http://imgur.com/R3LbkB4.png)

Each point has a position.

We can name the points:

![three points, labelled a, b and c](http://imgur.com/mo1U6wd.png)

We'll usually use lowercase letters like $a$ or $b$ for points.

# Vectors
A vector has a direction, and a magnitude. You can think of the magnitude as the length of the vector.

![the vector v](http://imgur.com/F4UBelR.png)

We also give vectors names. Usually a letter in boldface (like $\textbf{v}$), or with a little bar over it (like $\bar{v}$). We'll enclose a vector in bars to denote its magnitude: $|\textbf{v}|$. 

Vectors do not have a position which means these: 

![five copies of the same vector in different positions](http://imgur.com/oKg9TUq.png)

are all the _same_ vector, since they all point in the same direction, and have the same magnitude. As an example to make this fact more intuitive, "one mile north" is a vector: it has a direction (north) and a magnitude (1 mile), and you can go a mile north from (almost) anywhere in the world.


If we start at a point, we can add a vector to it to go to another point. 

![the point b + the vector v = the point c](http://imgur.com/p41DKAT.png)

We write this as $b + \textbf{v} = c$. This just says: "If you start at $b$, and move along the vector $\textbf{v}$, you will end up at $c$."

We can rearrange this algebraically to get $\textbf{v} = c - b$. You can think of this as saying that $\textbf{v}$ is the difference between the points $c$ and $b$. We can use this to describe vectors we haven't named yet. 

![the vector v = c-b, and the vector b-a](http://imgur.com/vYNRpKC.png)

# Vector addition
Two vectors can also be added together, which will give us a new vector. 

![vector addition: u + v = w](http://imgur.com/M0fB2R1.png)

$$\textbf{u} + \textbf{v} = \textbf{w}$$

If we write these vectors as the differences between two points, we can see that the algebra gives us the same result!

![vector addition: (b-a) + (c-b) = c-a](http://imgur.com/hJi77Fn.png)

$$(b-a) + (c-b) = c -b + b -a = c-a$$

The math for vectors was designed so that things which are true algebraically are also true geometrically, and vice versa. 

Vector addition also satisfies the commutative property and the associative property. For any three vectors $\textbf{u}$, $\textbf{v}$ and $\textbf{w}$, the following hold: $$\textbf{u} + \textbf{v} = \textbf{v} + \textbf{u}$$
$$(\textbf{u}+\textbf{v})+\textbf{w}=\textbf{u}+(\textbf{v}+\textbf{w})$$  Try drawing pictures of these yourself so you can see why it is true geometrically. 



# Scaling vectors
What happens when we add the same vector to itself? 

![v + v = 2v](http://imgur.com/suFT4Kk.png)

We get a vector in the same direction, but with twice the magnitude! Algebraically, we can depict this as $\textbf{v} + \textbf{v} = 2\textbf{v}$. 

In general, we can scale a vector by any amount we want. The number we scale it by is called a scalar. 

![v scaled by various amounts](http://imgur.com/GvqMnxk.png)

We can write this as $n\textbf{v}$, with $n$ being the scalar. 

One handy fact is that if we scale a vector, and then scale it again, the resulting vector will be scaled by the product of the two scalars. In algebra: $n(m\textbf{v}) = (nm)\textbf{v}$. Since these are the same, there's no need to keep the parenthesis, we can just write $nm\textbf{v}$ and the meaning will be clear.

## Reverse
One thing that comes in handy a lot is reversing a vector. To see what this should be algebraically, we'll write the vector as the difference of points: $\textbf{v} = b -a$. Remember, this means $\textbf{v}$ is the vector that will take you from $a$ to $b$. 

![the vector b-a and its reverse, a-b](http://imgur.com/FOkPG2T.png)

The reverse will be the vector that will take you from $b$ to $a$, so $a - b$, which is $-(b -a)= -\textbf{v}$.

So to reverse a vector, just scale it by $-1$. This can be combined with the product rule for scalars to scale a vector by any negative number!
 
## The zero vector
If we scale any vector by $0$, we get a special vector called the zero vector. $0\textbf{v} = \textbf{0}$. We write the zero vector in bold still to remind ourselves it's still a vector. 

![the zero vector](http://imgur.com/mKlfzr4.png)

As you can see, this vector is special because it has no direction, just a magnitude which is zero. And even though it looks like a point, it is different because it doesn't even have a position!

If we add the zero vector to any point, we just get the same point: $a + \textbf{0} = a$. If we add the zero vector to any vector, we get the same vector: $\textbf{v} + \textbf{0} = \textbf{v}$. If we add a vector to its reverse, we get the zero vector: $\textbf{v} - \textbf{v} = 0$. 

It's the additive identity for vector addition, just like zero is the additive identity for ordinary addition. This similarity is the reason we call it the zero vector. 

## Distributivity
What happens to the sum of two vectors if we scale them by the same scalar? Here's an illustration for $\textbf{u} +\textbf{v} = \textbf{w}$, which are then scaled by $2$.
 
![if u + v = w, then 2u + 2v = 2w](http://imgur.com/Vaj8Olj.png)

We can see that $2\textbf{u} + 2\textbf{v} = 2\text{w}$, the sum is scaled by the same amount as well!

The same thing is true for any scalar. Vector addition and multiplication by scalars obey the distributive law from algebra. For any scalar $n$, and any vectors $\textbf{u}$ and $\textbf{v}$:
 $$n\textbf{u} + n\textbf{v} = n(\textbf{u} + \textbf{v})$$

# Three dimensions and beyond
All of the same algebraic laws work in three dimensions too. As a visual example:

![x - y - z = d](http://imgur.com/NUD1y0v.png)

$$\textbf{x} - \textbf{y} - \textbf{z} = \textbf{d}$$ 

This is really helpful when doing calculations because it is a lot harder to draw things in three dimensions, but the algebra stays at about the same level of difficulty. It's even more helpful when doing work that requires four, or even more dimensions, where it is almost impossible to draw them!

----------
Next, let's see if there's a good way to multiply vectors.
